# PR Conventions

## Commit / PR Title — Conventional Commits

Format: `<type>(<scope>): <imperative summary>`

| type | When to use |
|---|---|
| feat | New feature |
| fix | Bug fix |
| refactor | Refactor without behavior change |
| perf | Performance improvement |
| test | Add/modify tests |
| docs | Docs only |
| build | Build system, dependencies |
| ci | CI/CD |
| chore | Other chores |

Rules:
- Imperative mood: "add", "remove", "update" (NOT "added", "adding").
- ≤ 72 chars.
- DO NOT end with a period.
- English only (commit history searchability).

## PR Description — required sections

1. **Why** — link spec + 1–2 sentences on business goal.
2. **What** — bullet list of main changes.
3. **Impact** — 🟢/🟡/🟠/🔴 + affected modules.
4. **How to test** — concrete steps.
5. **Spec** — BD + DDD links.
6. **Checklist** — spec FINAL, tests, review-staged, recheck-release, docs, feature flag, telemetry.
7. **Rollback plan** — required for 🟠/🔴 impact.
8. **Review focus** — guide reviewer to risky areas.

## Tri-lingual delivery
PR description ships in 3 languages: EN (canonical) + VI + JP, using collapsible `<details>` blocks. Title and commit body remain English only.

## PR size
- < 200 lines diff: ideal.
- 200–500: acceptable.
- > 500: needs strong justification.
